      "doNotMiss": [
        "Klavikula arkasındaki kanamaların komprese edilemeyeceğini, bu nedenle ciddi koagülopatisi olanlarda bu bloğun yüksek riskli olduğunu"
      ],
      "whenToEscalate": [
        "Blok sonrası pnömotoraks şüphesi varsa (solunum seslerinde azalma, göğüs ağrısı), acil akciğer grafisi çekin ve solunum sıkıntısı belirginse göğüs tüpü veya iğne dekompresyonu hazırlığı yapın"
      ],
      "referencesToShow": [
        "ASRA Deep Block Anticoagulation Guidelines.",
        "Miller's Anesthesia, 9th Edition."
      ],
      "safetyLevel": "urgent"
    },
    "en": {
      "notASubstituteWarning": "This response does not replace clinical judgment. Base decisions on your clinical assessment.",
      "conversationalText": "Supraclavicular block targets the divisions of the brachial plexus and is highly effective for elbow, forearm, and hand surgeries. It is often called the 'spinal of the upper limb'. The primary anatomical risk is pneumothorax due to the close proximity of the pleura.\n\nComplications and Precautions:\n1. Pneumothorax: The pleura, first rib, subclavian artery, and needle tip must be visualized continuously under ultrasound.\n2. LAST: High risk due to subclavian artery proximity.\n3. Phrenic Nerve Block: Occurs in approximately 30-50% of cases (lower than interscalene but still significant in respiratory-compromised patients).\n4. Anticoagulation: Because the site is deep and non-compressible (behind the clavicle), strictly follow ASRA deep block guidelines for anticoagulated patients.",
      "immediateRedFlags": [
        "Sudden chest pain, dry cough, and shortness of breath during or hours after the procedure (pneumothorax).",
        "Tinnitus, metallic taste, or seizures (LAST).",
        "Rapidly expanding hematoma under the clavicle."
      ],
      "missingCriticalInformation": [
        "The patient's current coagulation profile or anticoagulant intake",
        "Clear visualization of the first rib and pleura on the ultrasound monitor"
      ],
      "likelyClinicalCategoriesToConsider": [
        "Supraclavicular Block Risks",
        "Pneumothorax Prevention Techniques",
        "Deep and Non-Compressible Block Safety"
      ],
      "suggestedNextStepsGeneral": [
        "Direct the needle from lateral to medial, using the first rib as a physical shield to protect the underlying pleura.",
        "Keep the subclavian artery and pleura in clear view at all times.",
        "Ensure adherence to ASRA 2025 guidelines for deep/non-compressible nerve blocks in patients on anticoagulants."
      ],
      "relatedAlgorithms": [
        {
          "id": "supraclavicular_block",
          "titleTr": "Supraclavicular Block"
        },
        {
          "id": "pneumothorax",
          "titleTr": "Pneumothorax Management"
        },
        {
          "id": "last_management",
          "titleTr": "LAST Algorithm"
        }
      ],
      "relatedCalculators": [
        {
          "id": "local_anesthetic_max_dose",
          "titleTr": "LA Max Dose"
        },
        {
          "id": "anticoagulation_table",
          "titleTr": "Anticoagulation Table"
        }
      ],
      "relatedDrugCards": [
        {
          "id": "ropivacaine",
          "titleTr": "Ropivacaine"
        },
        {
          "id": "bupivacaine",
          "titleTr": "Bupivacaine"
        },
        {
          "id": "lidocaine",
          "titleTr": "Lidocaine"
        }
      ],
      "doNotMiss": [
        "Bleeding behind the clavicle cannot be compressed; therefore, severe coagulopathy is a strong relative contraindication"
      ],
      "whenToEscalate": [
        "If pneumothorax is suspected post-procedure, order an immediate chest X-ray and prepare for needle decompression or chest tube placement if symptomatic"
      ],
      "referencesToShow": [
        "ASRA Deep Block Anticoagulation Guidelines.",
        "Miller's Anesthesia, 9th Edition."
      ],
      "safetyLevel": "urgent"
    }
  },
  {
    "id": "infraclavicular_block",
    "category": "clinical_scenarios",
    "keywords": [
      "block",
      "blok",
      "infraclavicular",
      "infraklaviküler"
    ],
    "question_tr": "Infraklaviküler blok",
    "question_en": "Infraclavicular block",
    "safetyLevel": "elective",
    "tr": {
      "notASubstituteWarning": "Bu yanıt klinik kararın yerine geçmez. Klinik değerlendirmenizi temel alın.",
      "conversationalText": "İnfraklaviküler blok, brakiyal pleksusun kordlarını (lateral, medial, posterior) aksiller arter komşuluğunda hedefler. Dirsek, ön kol ve el cerrahilerinde tercih edilir.\n\nKlinik Özellikler:\n1. Kateter Stabilizasyonu: Supraklaviküler bölgeye göre daha kararlı bir kateter yerleşimi sunar, çünkü göğüs duvarı kateteri sabitlemek için geniş bir alan sağlar.\n2. Anatomik Avantajlar: Frenik sinir etkilenmesi ve pnömotoraks riski supraklaviküler yaklaşma göre daha düşüktür.\n3. Omuz Cerrahisi: Omuz cerrahisi analjezisi için yeterli değildir (aksiller sinir lifleri daha proksimalde ayrılır).\n4. Zorluklar: Aksiller arter çevresindeki kordların (lateral, posterior, medial) derinliği nedeniyle ultrasonla görüntülenmesi ve iğne yönlendirmesi daha zordur. Derin enjeksiyon nedeniyle LAST ve hematom takibi önemlidir.",
      "immediateRedFlags": [
        "Derin enjeksiyon sırasında aksiller arter ponksiyonu ve komprese edilemeyen hematom.",
        "Tinnitus, perioral uyuşma ve ajitasyon (LAST belirtileri).",
        "Kateterin yerinden çıkması veya enfeksiyon belirtileri."
      ],
      "missingCriticalInformation": [
        "Hastanın anatomik yapısı ve aksiller arter derinliği",
        "Kateterin hedeflenen kordlara olan mesafesi"
      ],
      "likelyClinicalCategoriesToConsider": [
        "İnfraklaviküler Yaklaşım Avantajları",
        "Sürekli Periferik Kateter Güvenliği",
        "Derin Brakiyal Pleksus Blokları"
      ],
      "suggestedNextStepsGeneral": [
        "Aksiller arterin arkasındaki posterior kordu net hedefleyin (lokal anesteziğin arterin arkasına yayılması 'U' şeklinde dağılım sağlar).",
        "Kateter yerleştirilecekse tünelleme yöntemiyle sabitlemeyi düşünün.",
        "Derin bir blok olması nedeniyle antikoagülan kullanımını kontrol edin."
      ],
      "relatedAlgorithms": [
        {
          "id": "infraclavicular_block",
          "titleTr": "İnfraklaviküler Blok"
        },
        {
          "id": "continuous_catheter",
          "titleTr": "Sürekli Periferik Kateter"
        }
      ],
      "relatedCalculators": [
        {
          "id": "local_anesthetic_max_dose",
          "titleTr": "LA Maksimum Doz"
        }
      ],
      "relatedDrugCards": [
        {
          "id": "ropivacaine",
          "titleTr": "Ropivakain"
        },
        {
          "id": "bupivacaine",
          "titleTr": "Bupivakain"
        }
      ],
      "doNotMiss": [
        "Omuz cerrahisi için infraklaviküler bloğun yetersiz kalacağını, bu cerrahide interskalen veya supraskapuler blok tercih edilmesi gerektiğini"
      ],
      "whenToEscalate": [
        "Aksiller arter ponksiyonu sonrası derin hematom gelişirse veya nörolojik defisit gözlenirse cerrahi konsültasyon isteyin ve antikoagülanları askıya alın"
      ],
      "referencesToShow": [
        "ASRA Guidelines on Infraclavicular Block.",
        "Miller's Anesthesia, 9th Edition."
      ],
      "safetyLevel": "elective"
    },
    "en": {
      "notASubstituteWarning": "This response does not replace clinical judgment. Base decisions on your clinical assessment.",
      "conversationalText": "Infraclavicular block targets the cords of the brachial plexus (lateral, medial, posterior) in relation to the axillary artery. It is used for elbow, forearm, and hand surgeries.\n\nClinical Characteristics:\n1. Catheter Stability: Offers a more stable catheter placement than supraclavicular blocks, as the chest wall provides a broad surface for secure fixation.\n2. Anatomic Advantages: Lower incidence of phrenic nerve block and pneumothorax compared with the supraclavicular approach.\n3. Shoulder Surgery: Inadequate for shoulder surgery (the axillary nerve branches off more proximally).\n4. Technical Challenges: The cords are deeper, making ultrasound visualization and needle alignment more challenging. Monitor for LAST and hematoma due to depth and adjacent vascularity.",
      "immediateRedFlags": [
        "Axillary artery puncture with deep, non-compressible hematoma formation.",
        "Tinnitus, perioral numbness, or agitation (LAST signs).",
        "Catheter migration or signs of local infection."
      ],
      "missingCriticalInformation": [
        "The patient's chest wall anatomy and axillary artery depth",
        "The target cord distance and visualization clarity"
      ],
      "likelyClinicalCategoriesToConsider": [
        "Infraclavicular Approach Advantages",
        "Continuous Peripheral Catheter Safety",
        "Deep Brachial Plexus Block Techniques"
      ],
      "suggestedNextStepsGeneral": [
        "Target the posterior cord behind the axillary artery to ensure a 'U-shaped' local anesthetic spread around the vessel.",
        "Consider tunneling the catheter to prevent accidental dislodgement.",
        "Verify anticoagulation status before performing this deep block."
      ],
      "relatedAlgorithms": [
        {
          "id": "infraclavicular_block",
          "titleTr": "Infraclavicular Block"
        },
        {
          "id": "continuous_catheter",
          "titleTr": "Continuous Peripheral Catheter"
        }
      ],
      "relatedCalculators": [
        {
          "id": "local_anesthetic_max_dose",
          "titleTr": "LA Max Dose"
        }
      ],
      "relatedDrugCards": [
        {
          "id": "ropivacaine",
          "titleTr": "Ropivacaine"
        },
        {
          "id": "bupivacaine",
          "titleTr": "Bupivacaine"
        }
      ],
      "doNotMiss": [
        "Infraclavicular blocks are insufficient for shoulder analgesia; use interscalene or suprascapular blocks instead"
      ],
      "whenToEscalate": [
        "In case of deep hematoma formation or progressive neurological deficit after arterial puncture, obtain an urgent surgical consult and hold anticoagulants"
      ],
      "referencesToShow": [
        "ASRA Guidelines on Infraclavicular Block.",
        "Miller's Anesthesia, 9th Edition."
      ],
      "safetyLevel": "elective"
    }
  },
  {
    "id": "axillary_block",
    "category": "clinical_scenarios",
    "keywords": [
      "aksiller",
      "axillary",
