          "id": "ropivacaine",
          "titleTr": "Ropivakain"
        },
        {
          "id": "bupivacaine",
          "titleTr": "Bupivakain"
        }
      ],
      "doNotMiss": [
        "Paravertebral alanın nöraksiyel alanla doğrudan foramenler yoluyla bağlantılı olduğunu ve kazara epidural yayılım riski taşıdığını"
      ],
      "whenToEscalate": [
        "Blok sonrası kontrolsüz hipotansiyon, çift taraflı uyuşma ve dispne gelişirse (epidural/spinal kaçış), hava yolunu koruyun, IV sıvı/vazopressör başlayın ve kriz protokolünü uygulayın"
      ],
      "referencesToShow": [
        "ASRA Deep Block Anticoagulation Guidelines.",
        "Miller's Anesthesia, 9th Edition."
      ],
      "safetyLevel": "urgent"
    },
    "en": {
      "notASubstituteWarning": "This response does not replace clinical judgment. Base decisions on your clinical assessment.",
      "conversationalText": "Paravertebral block (PVB) provides highly effective unilateral segmental analgesia by depositing local anesthetic in the thoracic paravertebral space, blocking the ipsilateral spinal nerve roots.\n\nClinical Characteristics:\n1. Indications: Gold standard for thoracotomy, major breast surgery (mastectomy with axillary dissection), rib fractures, and video-assisted thoracoscopic surgery (VATS).\n2. Anatomical Proximity: The paravertebral space is bounded anteriorly by the pleura, posteriorly by the superior costotransverse ligament, and medially by the vertebral body. Proximity to the pleura, neuraxial space, and intercostal vessels makes it technically demanding.\n3. Risks: Pneumothorax (1-5%), accidental epidural or intrathecal spread (risk of high/total spinal), hypotension (sympathetic blockade), intercostal artery puncture, hematoma, and LAST.\n4. Anticoagulation: Because it is a deep, non-compressible site close to the neuraxial space, strictly adhere to ASRA neuraxial guidelines for patients on anticoagulants.",
      "immediateRedFlags": [
        "Sudden dry cough and shortness of breath during needle positioning (pleural puncture).",
        "Rapidly ascending sensory/motor block with hypotension (accidental epidural/intrathecal migration).",
        "Expanding deep paravertebral hematoma after vascular puncture."
      ],
      "missingCriticalInformation": [
        "The exact timing of the patient's last dose of anticoagulants",
        "The patient's baseline lung reserve and ability to tolerate a pneumothorax"
      ],
      "likelyClinicalCategoriesToConsider": [
        "Thoracic Segmental Analgesia",
        "Paravertebral Space Anatomy",
        "Near-Neuraxial Block Safety"
      ],
      "suggestedNextStepsGeneral": [
        "Visualize the transverse process, superior costotransverse ligament, and pleura clearly using ultrasound.",
        "Advance the needle through the ligament and observe downward displacement of the pleura (pleural depression) during injection.",
        "Verify the patient's coagulation and anticoagulant schedule strictly using ASRA neuraxial criteria."
      ],
      "relatedAlgorithms": [
        {
          "id": "paravertebral_block",
          "titleTr": "Paravertebral Block"
        },
        {
          "id": "pneumothorax",
          "titleTr": "Pneumothorax Management"
        },
        {
          "id": "high_spinal",
          "titleTr": "High Spinal Algorithm"
        }
      ],
      "relatedCalculators": [
        {
          "id": "local_anesthetic_max_dose",
          "titleTr": "LA Max Dose"
        },
        {
          "id": "anticoagulation_table",
          "titleTr": "Anticoagulation Table"
        }
      ],
      "relatedDrugCards": [
        {
          "id": "ropivacaine",
          "titleTr": "Ropivacaine"
        },
        {
          "id": "bupivacaine",
          "titleTr": "Bupivacaine"
        }
      ],
      "doNotMiss": [
        "The paravertebral space communicates directly with the epidural space via the intervertebral foramina, posing a risk of epidural spread"
      ],
      "whenToEscalate": [
        "If bilateral numbness, severe hypotension, and dyspnea occur post-block, treat as high spinal: support airway, administer IV fluids/vasopressors, and initiate rescue protocols"
      ],
      "referencesToShow": [
        "ASRA Deep Block Anticoagulation Guidelines.",
        "Miller's Anesthesia, 9th Edition."
      ],
      "safetyLevel": "urgent"
    }
  },
  {
    "id": "ql_block",
    "category": "clinical_scenarios",
    "keywords": [
      "block",
