    "en": {
      "notASubstituteWarning": "This response does not replace clinical judgment. Base decisions on your clinical assessment.",
      "conversationalText": "Popliteal sciatic block targets the sciatic nerve in the popliteal fossa just proximal to its bifurcation into the tibial and common peroneal nerves. It is the preferred technique for foot and ankle surgeries.\n\nClinical Characteristics:\n1. Indications: Provides outstanding analgesia for foot, ankle, Achilles tendon repairs, and distal tibia surgeries.\n2. Saphenous Nerve Requirement: The sensory input of the medial ankle and medial border of the foot is supplied by the saphenous nerve (a branch of the femoral nerve). If the surgical incision involves the medial aspect, a saphenous nerve block (at the adductor canal or below-knee level) must be added.\n3. Risks: Nerve injury, popliteal vessel puncture, deep hematoma, LAST, and delayed motor recovery affecting postoperative mobility.\n4. Diabetic Neuropathy: In patients with diabetic neuropathy or pre-existing neurological deficits, document a detailed baseline sensory-motor status before block placement.",
      "immediateRedFlags": [
        "Severe radiating paresthesia or electric shock sensation in the foot during needle positioning (intraneural contact).",
        "Tense, non-compressible hematoma in the popliteal fossa after arterial puncture.",
        "Motor paralysis persisting beyond 24-36 hours."
      ],
      "missingCriticalInformation": [
