          "titleTr": "Ropivakain"
        },
        {
          "id": "epinephrine",
          "titleTr": "Epinefrin"
        }
      ],
      "doNotMiss": [
        "Epidural kateter takılı hastada beklenmeyen bacak güçsüzlüğü geliştiğinde, bunun sadece ilaç etkisi değil, epidural hematom olabileceğini ve acil dekompresyon gerektiğini"
      ],
      "whenToEscalate": [
        "Hastada ani başlayan, ilerleyici motor kayıp ve mesane/rektum disfonksiyonu gözlenirse, epidural hematom şüphesiyle acil MRI planlayın ve beyin cerrahisini çağırın"
      ],
      "referencesToShow": [
        "ASRA Neuraxial Guidelines.",
        "Miller's Anesthesia, 9th Edition."
      ],
      "safetyLevel": "urgent"
    },
    "en": {
      "notASubstituteWarning": "This response does not replace clinical judgment. Base decisions on your clinical assessment.",
      "conversationalText": "Epidural anesthesia and analgesia safety depends on selecting the correct anatomical level, strict adherence to anticoagulation guidelines, aseptic technique, test dose administration, fractionated dosing, and close clinical monitoring.\n\nSafety Protocols and Steps:\n1. Placement Documentation: Carefully document any paresthesia, blood return, or CSF leak during the procedure.\n2. Test Dose: Always aspirate before any injection. Use an epinephrine-containing test dose (e.g. 3 mL of 1.5% Lidocaine with 1:200,000 Epinephrine) to rule out accidental intravascular or intrathecal placement. Monitor for a heart rate spike or sudden motor block.\n3. Dosing: Always inject large volumes fractionally (3-5 mL increments) and slowly.\n4. Complication Monitoring: Monitor for hypotension, high block level, respiratory depression, and LAST.\n5. Epidural Hematoma: Any unexpected dense or progressive motor block, or new neurological deficit, requires immediate evaluation for epidural hematoma or catheter migration into the subarachnoid space.\n6. Catheter Removal: Catheter insertion and removal timing must follow ASRA anticoagulation protocols strictly.",
      "immediateRedFlags": [
        "Heart rate increase > 20 bpm or sudden BP spike within 60 seconds of test dose (inadvertent intravascular catheter).",
        "Onset of dense lower extremity motor block within 3-5 minutes of test dose (accidental subarachnoid migration).",
        "Progressive motor weakness, numbness, and severe back pain (Epidural Hematoma - surgical emergency!)."
      ],
      "missingCriticalInformation": [
        "The patient's anticoagulant schedule (last dose and next planned dose)",
        "The exact length of the catheter left in the epidural space (recommended: 3-5 cm)"
      ],
      "likelyClinicalCategoriesToConsider": [
        "Epidural Catheter Safety Protocols",
        "Epidural Hematoma Early Detection",
        "Test Dose and Dose Fractionation"
      ],
      "suggestedNextStepsGeneral": [
        "Aspirate the catheter thoroughly before every dose to check for blood or CSF.",
        "Administer the test dose and observe the ECG and lower limb motor function for 5 minutes.",
        "Maintain strict adherence to ASRA timelines during catheter removal."
      ],
      "relatedAlgorithms": [
